217	  <main id="main" class="wrap">
218	    <section id="what">
219	      <h2>What Scrum is</h2>
220	      <p>Scrum is a lightweight framework that helps teams deliver value through iterative work, frequent inspection, and adaptation. It defines a small set of accountabilities, events, and artifacts — and leaves the details of how the work gets done to the team.</p>
221	    </section>
222	
223	    <section id="when">
224	      <h2>When it helps</h2>
225	      <p>Scrum fits complex problems where requirements and solutions are uncertain and need to be discovered through delivery. It helps when a team needs a steady cadence to ship something useful, learn from it, and adjust — rather than committing up front to a fixed plan.</p>
226	    </section>
227	
228	    <section id="roles">
229	      <h2>Roles (accountabilities)</h2>
230	      <p class="lede">A Scrum Team has three accountabilities — together they own delivering value each Sprint.</p>
231	      <div class="grid">
232	        <article class="card">
233	          <h3>Product Owner</h3>
234	          <p>Accountable for maximizing the value of the product by managing the Product Backlog.</p>
235	        </article>
236	        <article class="card">
237	          <h3>Scrum Master</h3>
238	          <p>Accountable for the team's effectiveness and for establishing Scrum as defined in the Scrum Guide.</p>
239	        </article>
240	        <article class="card">
241	          <h3>Developers</h3>
242	          <p>Accountable for creating a usable Increment that meets the Definition of Done every Sprint.</p>
243	        </article>
244	      </div>
245	    </section>
246	
247	    <section id="events">
248	      <h2>Events</h2>
249	      <p class="lede">Five time-boxed events create regularity and remove the need for other meetings.</p>
250	      <div class="grid">
251	        <article class="card">
252	          <h3>Sprint</h3>
253	          <p>A fixed, time-boxed container (one month or less) inside which all the other Scrum events happen and an Increment is created.</p>
254	        </article>
255	        <article class="card">
256	          <h3>Sprint Planning</h3>
257	          <p>Initiates the Sprint by defining why it is valuable, what can be done, and how the chosen work will get done.</p>
258	        </article>
259	        <article class="card">
260	          <h3>Daily Scrum</h3>
261	          <p>A 15-minute event for Developers to inspect progress toward the Sprint Goal and adapt the plan for the next day.</p>
262	        </article>
263	        <article class="card">
264	          <h3>Sprint Review</h3>
265	          <p>Inspects the outcome of the Sprint with stakeholders and determines future adaptations to the Product Backlog.</p>
266	        </article>
267	        <article class="card">
268	          <h3>Sprint Retrospective</h3>
269	          <p>Closes the Sprint by planning ways to increase quality and effectiveness in how the team works together.</p>
270	        </article>
271	      </div>
272	    </section>
273	
274	    <section id="artifacts">
275	      <h2>Artifacts</h2>
276	      <p class="lede">Each artifact represents work or value, and each has a commitment that gives it focus.</p>
277	      <div class="grid">
278	        <article class="card">
279	          <h3>Product Backlog</h3>
280	          <p>An ordered list of what is needed to improve the product. Its commitment is the Product Goal.</p>
281	        </article>
282	        <article class="card">
283	          <h3>Sprint Backlog</h3>
284	          <p>The plan by and for the Developers — the Sprint Goal, the selected Product Backlog items, and how to deliver them.</p>
285	        </article>
286	        <article class="card">
287	          <h3>Increment</h3>
288	          <p>A concrete step toward the Product Goal. Each Increment is additive to all prior Increments and must be usable.</p>
289	        </article>
290	        <article class="card">
291	          <h3>Definition of Done</h3>
292	          <p>The shared standard of quality an Increment must meet to be considered complete and releasable.</p>
293	        </article>
294	      </div>
295	    </section>
296	
297	    <section id="sprint">
298	      <h2>The Sprint: a time-boxed container</h2>
299	      <p>The Sprint is the heartbeat of Scrum. It is a fixed-length cycle, one month or less, during which the team turns ideas into a usable Increment. Sprint Planning opens it, the Daily Scrum keeps it on track, and the Sprint Review and Retrospective close it — same length, same rhythm, every time.</p>
